The paper discusses the Restricted Isometry Property (RIP) in compressed sensing and its limitations in real-world applications. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT), Signal Processing (cs.SP), Computer Engineering (cs.CE), Multimedia (cs.MM), or Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-categories. The paper specifically mentions applications such as Magnetic Resonance Imaging (MRI), Computerized Tomography, Electron Microscopy, Radio Interferometry, and Fluorescence Microscopy, which are commonly associated with the Signal Processing and Computer Vision sub-categories. Therefore, cs.SP and cs.CV are the most likely sub-categories. However, the paper also introduces a new framework based on a generalised RIP-like definition, which suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the Information Theory and Computer Engineering sub-categories. Finally, the paper concludes by providing examples that demonstrate the optimality of the results obtained, which may be relevant to the Multimedia sub-category.
